n’s Northanger Abbey and its afterlives, the final works of Virginia Woolf, and late twentieth-century film and music videos from the United States. The final chapter examines the treatment of women's bodies and vulnerability in both political theory and recent electoral politics, arguing that they share a common thread of misogyny rooted in the idea of the medieval past, and that one way to challenge that misogyny is by looking at complex feminist engagements with that same past, both real and imagined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist criticism. 0aMiddle Ages in literature. 0aMiddle Ages in motion pictures. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChaucer.  aEmbodied medievalism.  aJane Austen.  aNorthanger Abbey.  aVirginia Woolf.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311133235240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781802701531?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781802701531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781802701531/original  a978-3-11-133235-2  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles